 inequalities in living conditions, incarceration rates, family systems, and opportunities. These racial disparities often cut across social class boundaries and have gender-specific consequences. Bringing together data from existing quantitative and qualitative research with new archival and interview data, this book advances research in the fields of families, race-ethnicity, and medical sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxHealth and hygienezUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxMedical carezUnited States. 0aAfrican Americans. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezUnited States. 0aHealth and race. 0aHealth services accessibilityzUnited States. 0aHealth services accessibility. 0aMedical care. 0aMedical policy. 0aMinoritiesxMedical carezUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Public Health.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311119643540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447322832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447322832/original  a978-3-11-119643-5  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles